ABSTRACT

ARPx (ARP Analyzer Pro) is a Python-based network security toolkit developed by students of GLA University, Mathura, as part of the B.Tech. Mini Project for the Cyber Security & Forensics specialization. The tool demonstrates real-world Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) attack techniques and detection strategies in a controlled, educational environment using the Scapy packet manipulation library. The Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) is an inherently insecure Layer 2 protocol that lacks authentication, making it vulnerable to cache-poisoning attacks. ARPx exploits this vulnerability in a controlled lab environment to illustrate the complete lifecycle of an ARP-based attack.
The tool provides three core capabilities: (1) Network Scanning — discovering all active hosts on a subnet using ARP broadcast packets; (2) ARP Spoofing Simulation — poisoning ARP caches to simulate a MitM attack and intercept traffic flow; and (3) ARP Spoof Detection — passively sniffing ARP traffic and alerting in real-time when MAC-to-IP inconsistencies are detected. A professional dark-themed graphical user interface (GUI) was built using Python Tkinter, with all network operations executing in background threads to maintain interface responsiveness.
Testing was conducted on an isolated VirtualBox Host-Only network using Kali Linux as the attacker machine and Windows 10 as the victim. All seven test cases passed successfully, including network scan verification, ARP cache poisoning confirmation, automatic ARP table restoration, and real-time detection. The project provides a strong academic foundation for understanding network-layer vulnerabilities, ethical hacking methodology, and the importance of network-level security controls in modern enterprise environments.

Keywords: ARP Spoofing, Man-in-the-Middle Attack, Network Security, Scapy, Python, Ethical Hacking, ARP Cache Poisoning, Intrusion Detection.


