CHAPTER 1 INTRODUCTION

1.1   Overview and Motivation
ARPx (ARP Analyzer Pro) is a Python-based network security toolkit developed by students of GLA University, Mathura. It demonstrates real-world Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) attack techniques and detection strategies in a controlled, educational environment.
The motivation behind ARPx stems from the growing importance of network-level security in modern computing. The Address Resolution Protocol (ARP), though foundational to local area network communication, was designed for speed and lacks any built-in authentication mechanism. This fundamental design flaw has been exploited by attackers for decades, yet many students and entry-level security professionals lack hands-on exposure to how such attacks work in practice.
By building a tool that both simulates and detects ARP spoofing, this project bridges the gap between theoretical knowledge and practical application, equipping students with a deeper understanding of Layer 2 network vulnerabilities.
1.2   Objective
The primary objectives of the ARPx project are as follows:
•	To implement a fully functional ARP network scanner capable of discovering all active hosts on a subnet using ARP broadcast packets.
•	To simulate an ARP Spoofing (MitM) attack in a controlled, isolated network environment, demonstrating cache poisoning on both the victim and gateway.
•	To develop a real-time ARP Spoof Detection module that passively sniffs traffic and alerts the user upon detecting IP-to-MAC mapping changes.
•	To design a professional, multi-threaded graphical user interface using Python Tkinter that remains responsive during all network operations.
•	To validate the tool through a structured testing methodology and document results as proof of concept.
1.3   Issues and Challenges
The development of ARPx encountered several technical and ethical challenges that required careful consideration and resolution:
•	Raw Socket Privileges: ARP packet crafting with Scapy requires root/administrator privileges. The tool is tightly coupled to Linux environments (specifically Kali Linux) where such access can be granted safely in a test setup.
•	Thread Safety: Running network operations alongside a Tkinter GUI introduces concurrency issues. All network calls were moved to background threads using threading.Thread and GUI updates were routed through root.after() to avoid race conditions.
•	ARP Restoration: When spoofing is stopped abruptly, victim and gateway ARP tables remain poisoned. Implementing reliable restoration logic required crafting and sending correct ARP replies multiple times to ensure tables are flushed.
•	Network Isolation: Ensuring testing was only performed on isolated virtual networks to prevent unintentional disruption of real network infrastructure was both a technical and ethical challenge.
1.4   Contribution
The key contributions of this project are:
•	A unified, open-source Python tool that combines scanning, attacking, and detecting in a single GUI application — no existing free tool offers all three in one interface designed explicitly for educational use.
•	A documented, reproducible test methodology with live ARP table evidence, providing a model for how network security tools can be validated in academic settings.
•	Responsible design — automatic ARP restoration on stop and no credential capture functionality — setting an ethical standard for student-built offensive security tools.
