CHAPTER 2 BACKGROUND & LITERATURE REVIEW

2.1   What is ARP?
The Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) is a Layer 2 protocol defined in RFC 826 (1982) used to map an IP address to a physical (MAC) address within a local area network. When a device wants to communicate with another device on the same subnet, it broadcasts an ARP Request: 'Who has IP X? Tell me your MAC address.' The target device responds with an ARP Reply containing its MAC address, and the requesting device caches this mapping for future use.
ARP operates at the Data Link Layer (Layer 2) of the OSI model and is fundamental to the operation of Ethernet networks. Every device on a network maintains an ARP cache — a table mapping IP addresses to MAC addresses — which it uses to avoid broadcasting for every packet sent.
2.2   Why is ARP Vulnerable?
ARP has no built-in authentication mechanism. Any device on a network can send a fake ARP Reply claiming any IP-to-MAC mapping, regardless of whether it received an ARP Request. Worse, most operating systems will accept and cache unsolicited ARP Replies (known as Gratuitous ARP), making the protocol trivially exploitable.
An attacker exploits this by performing the following steps:
•	Sending fake ARP Replies to the victim machine, mapping the gateway's IP address to the attacker's MAC address.
•	Sending fake ARP Replies to the gateway, mapping the victim's IP address to the attacker's MAC address.
•	The attacker's machine now sits in the middle of all traffic between the victim and the gateway — a classic Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) attack.
Related works in this domain include research by Whalen (2001) who first formally analyzed ARP poisoning attacks, and subsequent work by Ramachandran and Feamster (2006) on detecting ARP spoofing using flow-level analysis. Bruschi et al. (2003) proposed S-ARP, a secure extension to ARP using asymmetric cryptography, while more recent work has focused on SDN-based mitigation strategies.
2.3   Detection Strategy
ARPx implements a passive detection strategy based on ARP cache monitoring. The tool maintains an in-memory ARP table indexed by IP address. When a new ARP Reply is sniffed from the network, the tool compares the sender's MAC address against the cached value for that IP.
A sudden change in the MAC address associated with a known IP — particularly for high-value IPs like the default gateway — strongly indicates an active ARP spoofing attack. The tool raises an immediate real-time alert in the GUI console when such a change is detected. This approach is consistent with the detection methodology described by Whalen (2001) and does not require any modifications to the underlying network infrastructure.


CHAPTER 3 PROPOSED WORK

3.1   System Architecture
ARPx is organized into four loosely-coupled modules, each running as an independent thread within the main Tkinter event loop:
•	Network Scanner Module: Sends ARP broadcast packets (Ether(dst='ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff')/ARP(pdst=subnet)) to the target CIDR subnet and collects replies to build a host list.
•	ARP Spoofer Module: Continuously crafts and sends forged ARP Reply packets to both the target (victim) and gateway using Scapy's send() function at a configurable interval.
•	ARP Restoration Module: On stop, sends correctly crafted ARP Replies (with the real MAC addresses) multiple times to both victim and gateway to restore legitimate ARP table entries.
•	ARP Detection Module: Uses Scapy's sniff() function with an ARP filter to passively monitor traffic. Maintains an in-memory dict of {IP: MAC} and raises alerts on MAC changes.
3.2   Algorithm & Pseudo Code
3.2.1   ARP Spoofing Algorithm
The ARP spoofing algorithm operates as follows:
•	INPUT: target_ip, gateway_ip
•	Resolve target_mac = get_mac(target_ip) using ARP request
•	Resolve gateway_mac = get_mac(gateway_ip) using ARP request
•	REPEAT every 2 seconds until stopped:
•	  Send ARP Reply: op=2, pdst=target_ip, hwdst=target_mac, psrc=gateway_ip
•	  Send ARP Reply: op=2, pdst=gateway_ip, hwdst=gateway_mac, psrc=target_ip
•	ON STOP: Send 4 correction packets restoring real MAC mappings to both
3.2.2   Detection Algorithm
•	INITIALIZE: arp_cache = {}
•	SNIFF all ARP packets on the network interface
•	FOR each ARP Reply (op == 2) received:
•	  IF packet.psrc (sender IP) IN arp_cache:
•	    IF arp_cache[packet.psrc] != packet.hwsrc:
•	      ALERT: 'ARP Spoof Detected! IP [X] changed MAC from [A] to [B]'
•	  ELSE: arp_cache[packet.psrc] = packet.hwsrc
