5.2   Conclusion
ARPx successfully demonstrates the full lifecycle of an ARP-based Man-in-the-Middle attack — from host discovery and cache poisoning through to detection and remediation — within a professional interactive GUI. The tool was developed by Mayank Singh and Ketan Verma, and rigorously tested by Shashank Saini, Mayank Sharma, and Nitin Agrawal on an isolated virtual network.
The live test results captured in Figures 3 and 4 provide concrete proof that ARP spoofing was achieved successfully, and the detection module correctly identified the attack within the expected 2–4 second window. All seven test cases passed without exception.
The project provides a strong foundation for further study in network security, penetration testing, and ethical hacking. Future work could extend ARPx to support additional protocols (DNS spoofing, DHCP starvation), add HTTPS interception capabilities in controlled environments, or port the tool to a web-based interface for broader accessibility.
